eased","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1455":"1455","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sturmyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Sturmin</i>, probably a diminutive in <i>-in</i> of the Middle English personal name <i>Sturmi</i>, from Middle English <i>stormi</i> ‘stormy’ (Old French <i>estormi</i>), denoting a stormy temperament. Compare   Storm  .","English: variant of   Stearman   1 in which the main vowel of Middle English <i>ster(e)man</i>, <i>stir(e)man</i> has shortened, giving rise in the 17th century to the modern pronunciation variously spelled <i>-er-</i>, <i>-ir-</i>, and <i>-ur-</i>. In some cases the name may arise from the Middle English personal name <i>Stireman</i>, <i>Stereman</i> (Old Norse <i>Stȳreman</i>, originally a nickname from the Old Danish word for a helmsman or skipper); see   Stearman   1.","Americanized form of North German <b>Sturmann</b> or <b>Stuhrmann</b>, and of Dutch <b>Stuurman</b>: occupational name for a helmsman, from Middle Low German <i>stūren</i> ‘to steer’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."],"variants":[{"name":"Storm","meanings":["English, North German, Dutch, and Scandinavian: nickname for a man of blustery or stormy temperament, from Middle English, Middle Low German <i>storm</i>, Old Norse <i>stormr</i> ‘storm’.","Flemish and Dutch: occupational name for someone who sounded the alarm-bell, warning people for a coming storm, Middle Dutch <i>storm</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":105,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William Sturmyn was born in 1350, in England. He had at least 1 daughter with Joane. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1350–":"1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1455":"1455","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","England":"England"},"fi":{"1350–":"1350–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","England":"England"},"fr":{"1350–":"1350–Décédé","1350–Female":"1350–Décédée","1380–Female":"1380–Décédée","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1455":"145